      <div class="prose">
        <h2>The Canaletto Bridge</h2>
        <p>In 1754, the Venetian master Canaletto painted the old wooden bridge at Walton — one of only two paintings he made of English scenes during his extended stay in London. The bridge, a remarkable Chinese-inspired design by James Paine, was considered an engineering marvel of its era.</p>
        <p>The painting now hangs in the Yale Center for British Art in New Haven, Connecticut — rather a long journey for a view of the Surrey bank. You can see a reproduction at Walton library.</p>
        <p><a href="/community/news/walton-bridge-history/">Read the full history of Walton Bridge →</a></p>

        <h2>Whiteley Village</h2>
        <p>South of Hersham lies one of Britain's most extraordinary planned settlements — Whiteley Village, built between 1911 and 1921 as a model retirement community funded by the estate of Victorian retail magnate William Whiteley. Eight architects contributed buildings around a central octagonal green, all in a unified Arts and Crafts style, set within 225 acres of woodland.</p>
        <p>It's a Registered Historic Park and Garden, and most of its buildings are listed. It remains an active retirement community today and is open to respectful visitors.</p>
        <p><a href="/visit/things-to-do/whiteley-village/">Explore Whiteley Village →</a></p>

        <h2>Julie Andrews</h2>
        <p>Dame Julie Andrews, one of Britain's most beloved actresses and entertainers, was born in Walton-on-Thames in 1935 — though the family soon moved to Woodham. She grew up in the area and her stepfather Ted Andrews was a local performer. The connection to Walton is a point of quiet pride.</p>

        <h2>Hepworth Sculpture Walpole</h2>
        <p>The Hepworth Walpole is a remarkable public sculpture park housed in a converted Victorian pumping station and its grounds by the Thames. It holds an important collection of works from the estate of Dame Barbara Hepworth, displayed in an atmospheric setting that combines industrial heritage with art in the landscape.</p>

        <h2>Romans at Cowey Stakes</h2>
        <p>The area around Cowey Sale has a much older history — it's believed to be the site of one of Julius Caesar's crossings of the Thames during his invasion of Britain in 54 BC. The shallow ford was known as Cowey Stakes, named after stakes driven into the riverbed to impede cavalry crossings. The exact location is disputed by historians, but the connection adds a remarkable depth to what is now a pleasant riverside walk.</p>

        <h2>Wartime Walton</h2>
        <p>During the Second World War, Walton and the surrounding area played a significant role in aircraft production — the Vickers Supermarine works at nearby Weybridge produced Spitfire aircraft, and the area was a regular target for Luftwaffe bombing raids as a result. Several local buildings still bear marks from the period.</p>
      </div>

